  <!--background>This English hymn was originally published in 1904, on pp. 22-23 of Hymns of the Christian Life No. 3: for church worship, conventions, evangelistic services, prayer meetings, missionary meetings, revival servi­ces, res­cue mission work and Sunday schools, ed. and pub. by A. B. Simpson for Christian Publications of Harris­burg, PA (the Christian and Missionary Alliance publishing house); www.hymnary.org/hymn/HCL31904/page/22. The attribution is "Anon. Words of Chorus by A. B. S. [A. B. Simpson (1843-1919)]; Music by Margaret M. Simpson".<br>So Simpson evidently either didn't know the source of, or didn't attribute, the original which he published in English, adding the chorus (and the bottom half of the last verse) on his own.<br>Most of the lines in this wonderful hymn appear in 17th Century German, scattered here and there in a lengthy, fascinating tome of mystical poetry published in 1657, Der Cherubinischer Wandersmann, by one Johann Scheffler (pen-name 'Angelus Silesius'; there's a lot of background on him on the web). Portions of this remarkable collection of poems have been translated into English by various scholars (A. F. Kroeger, 1870; Paul Carus, 1908; J. E. Crawford Flitch, 1932; Julia Bilger, 1944; Frederick Franck, 1976; Maria Shrady, 1986).<br>Specifically, the two quatrains which Simpson used for verse 1 appear in book I (of 6), verses 61 and 62; those for verse 2 appear in book V, verse 199, and book II, verse 136; and the first half of verse 3 are in book V, verse 319. It seems that Simpson added not only the chorus, but also the last half of the last verse.</background-->
